is a collection of essays examining the rise of this cultural suspicion of mechanical imitations of life. Recent scholarship in post-humanism, post-colonialism, disability studies, post-modern feminism, eco-criticism, and radical Orientalism has significantly affected the critical discourse on this topic. In engaging with the work and thought of Coleridge, Poe, Hoffmann, Mary Shelley, and other Romantic luminaries, the contributors to this collection open new methodological approaches to understanding human interaction with technology that strives to simulate, supplement, or supplant organic life. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and technologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aLiterature and technologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aRobots in literature. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBurwick, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurwick, Frederick.1 aClason, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClason, Christopher R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemson, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEngelstein, Stefani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelstein, Stefani.1 aErickson, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, Peter.1 aFreeman, Kathryn S.1 aFreeman, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu